# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fmt-cpp-lib
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] In the C++ programming language, the **C++ Standard Library** is a collection of classes and functions, which are written in the core language and part of the C++ ISO Standard itself.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] The C++ Standard Library also incorporates most headers of the ISO C standard library ending with ".h", but their use was deprecated (reverted the deprecation since C++23).
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] C++23 instead considers these headers as useful for interoperability with C, and recommends against their usage outside of programs that are intended to be both valid C and C++ programs.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] No other headers in the C++ Standard Library end in ".h".
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] Features of the C++ Standard Library are declared within the `std` namespace.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] The C++ Standard Library is based upon conventions introduced by the Standard Template Library (STL), and has been influenced by research in generic programming and developers of the STL such as Alexander Stepanov and Meng Lee.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] Although the C++ Standard Library and the STL share many features, neither is a strict superset of the other.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] The design of the C++ standard library, much like the C standard library, is minimalistic, and contains only core features for programming, lacking most of the more specialised features offered by the Java standard library or C# standard library.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] For more features, some third-party libraries such as Boost libraries and POCO C++ Libraries, which offer additional features, may be used to supplement the standard library.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] An implementation for a C++ standard library header is described as "freestanding" if the execution of the program does not rely on an operating system.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] A noteworthy feature of the C++ Standard Library is that it not only specifies the syntax and semantics of generic algorithms, but also places requirements on their performance.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] These performance requirements often correspond to a well-known algorithm, which is expected but not required to be used.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] In most cases this requires linear time O(*n*) or linearithmic time O(*n* log *n*), but in some cases higher bounds are allowed, such as quasilinear time O(*n* log2 *n*) for stable sort (to allow in-place merge sort).
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] In other cases requirements remain laxer, such as selection, which is only required to be linear on average (as in quickselect), not requiring worst-case linear as in introselect.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] The C++ Standard Library underwent ISO standardization as part of the C++ ISO Standardization effort in the 1990s.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] Since 2011, it has been expanded and updated every three years with each revision of the C++ standard.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] C++20 specifies the introduction of standard library header units, and C++23 adds full module support for the standard library.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] The Apache C++ Standard Library is another open-source implementation.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] It was originally developed commercially by Rogue Wave Software and later donated to the Apache Software Foundation.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] However, after more than five years without a release, the board of the Apache Software Foundation decided to end this project and move it to Apache Attic.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] C++ was designed with systems programming and embedded, resource-constrained software and large systems in mind, with performance, efficiency, and flexibility of use as its design highlights.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] C++ is standardized by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), with the latest standard version ratified and published by ISO in October 2024 as *ISO/IEC 14882:2024* (informally known as C++23).
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] The C++ programming language was initially standardized in 1998 as *ISO/IEC 14882:1998*, which was then amended by the C++03, C++11, C++14, C++17, and C++20 standards.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] The next C++23 standard superseded these with new features and an enlarged standard library.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] Before the initial standardization in 1998, C++ was developed by Stroustrup at Bell Labs since 1979 as an extension of the C language; he wanted an efficient and flexible language similar to C that also provided high-level features for program organization.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] Since 2012, C++ has been on a three-year release schedule with C++29 as the next planned standard.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] In 1979, Bjarne Stroustrup, a Danish computer scientist, began work on "C with Classes", the predecessor to C++.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] The motivation for creating a new language originated from Stroustrup's experience in programming for his PhD thesis.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup found that Simula had features that were very helpful for large software development, but the language was too slow for practical use, while BCPL was fast but too low-level to be suitable for large software development.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] When Stroustrup started working in AT&T Bell Labs, he had the problem of analyzing the UNIX kernel with respect to distributed computing.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] Remembering his PhD experience, Stroustrup set out to enhance the C language with Simula-like features.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] C was chosen because it was general-purpose, fast, portable, and widely used.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] In addition to C and Simula's influences, other languages influenced this new language, including ALGOL 68, Ada, CLU, and ML.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] Initially, Stroustrup's "C with Classes" added features to the C compiler, Cpre, including classes, derived classes, strong typing, inlining, and default arguments.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] In 1982, Stroustrup began designing a cleaned-up and extended successor to C with Classes, using traditional compiler technology.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] The language was briefly called C84 before the name C++ was adopted; the name was suggested by Rick Mascitti and refers to C's `++` increment operator.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] The resulting language included virtual functions, function and operator overloading, references, `const`, improved type checking, user-controlled free-store memory allocation (`new`/`delete`), and BCPL-style single-line `//` comments.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup also designed and implemented Cfront, the C++ compiler front end, between spring 1982 and summer 1983.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] In 1984, Stroustrup implemented the first stream input/output library.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] The idea of providing an output operator rather than a named output function was suggested by Doug McIlroy (who had previously suggested Unix pipes).
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] In 1985, the first edition of *The C++ Programming Language* was released, which became the definitive reference for the language, as there was not yet an official standard.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] The first commercial implementation of C++ was released in October of the same year.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] In 1989, C++ 2.0 was released, followed by the updated second edition of *The C++ Programming Language* in 1991.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] New features in 2.0 included multiple inheritance, abstract classes, static member functions, const member functions, and protected members.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] In 1990, *The Annotated C++ Reference Manual* was published.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] This work became the basis for the future standard.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] Later feature additions included templates, exceptions, namespaces, new casts, and a Boolean type.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] In 1998, C++98 was released, standardizing the language, and a minor update (C++03) was released in 2003.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] After C++98, C++ evolved relatively slowly until, in 2011, the C++11 standard was released, adding numerous new features, enlarging the standard library further, and providing more facilities to C++ programmers.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] After a minor C++14 update released in December 2014, various new additions were introduced in C++17.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] After becoming finalized in February 2020, a draft of the C++20 standard was approved on 4 September 2020, and officially published on 15 December 2020.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] On January 3, 2018, Stroustrup was announced as the 2018 winner of the Charles Stark Draper Prize for Engineering, "for conceptualizing and developing the C++ programming language".
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] In December 2022, C++ ranked third on the TIOBE index, surpassing Java for the first time in the history of the index.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] As of November 2024, the language ranks second after Python, with Java being in third.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] In March 2025, Stroustrup issued a call for the language community to defend it.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] Since the language allows manual memory management, bugs that represent security risks such as buffer overflow may be introduced in programs when inadvertently misused by the programmer.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] According to Stroustrup, "the name signifies the evolutionary nature of the changes from C." This name is credited to Rick Mascitti (mid-1983) and was first used in December 1983.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] When Mascitti was questioned informally in 1992 about the naming, he indicated that it was given in a tongue-in-cheek spirit.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] The name comes from C's `++` operator (which increments the value of a variable) and a common naming convention of using "+" to indicate an enhanced computer program.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] During C++'s development period, the language had been referred to as "new C" and "C with Classes" before acquiring its final name.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] C++ is standardized by an ISO working group known as JTC1/SC22/WG21.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] The working group holds three week-long meetings each year.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] So far, it has published seven revisions of the C++ standard and is currently working on the next revision, C++26.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] In 1998, the ISO working group standardized C++ for the first time as *ISO/IEC 14882:1998*, which is informally known as *C++98*.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] In 2003, it published a new version of the C++ standard called *ISO/IEC 14882:2003*, which fixed problems identified in C++98.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] The next major revision of the standard was informally referred to as "C++0x", but it was not released until 2011.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] C++11 (14882:2011) included many additions to both the core language and the standard library.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] In 2014, C++14 (also known as C++1y) was released as a small extension to C++11, featuring mainly bug fixes and small improvements.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] The Draft International Standard ballot procedures completed in mid-August 2014.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] After C++14, a major revision C++17, informally known as C++1z, was completed by the ISO C++ committee in mid July 2017 and was approved and published in December 2017.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] More technical specifications are in development and pending approval.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] The C++ language has two main components: a direct mapping of hardware features provided primarily by the C subset, and zero-overhead abstractions based on those mappings.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup describes C++ as "a light-weight abstraction programming language [designed] for building and using efficient and elegant abstractions"; and "offering both hardware access and abstraction is the basis of C++.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] A hello world program that conforms to the C standard is also a valid C++ hello world program.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] The C++ standard specifies both the core language and the standard library.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] The library clauses describe the contents of the library, how a well-formed C++ program uses it, and the requirements placed on conforming implementations.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] The standard library is organized into areas such as language support, diagnostics, memory management, metaprogramming, general utilities, containers, iterators, ranges, algorithms, strings, text processing, numerics, time, input/output, and concurrency support.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] It also provides the facilities of the C standard library through C++ headers such as `<cstdio>` and `<cstdlib>`; except for names defined as macros in C, these declarations are placed in namespace `std`.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] Library facilities are traditionally made available by including standard headers, for example `#include <vector>`.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] Since C++20, importable standard library headers may also be imported as header units.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] C++23 added the named standard library modules `std` and `std.compat`: `std` exports declarations in namespace `std`, while `std.compat` also exports corresponding global namespace declarations for C library facilities.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] A major influence on the standard library was the Standard Template Library (STL), a generic programming library proposed to the C++ standards committee by Alexander Stepanov and Meng Lee in 1994.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] Its model of containers, iterators, and generic algorithms became part of the Standard C++ Library, although the standard library also includes many other facilities, such as input/output, localization, diagnostics, and the C library subset.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] The main aim is to efficiently and consistently write type and resource safe C++.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] Despite this, the guidelines are not endorsed by the ISO C++ standards committee and do not represent the consensus of the committee.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] The Core Guidelines were announced in the opening keynote at CPPCon 2015.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] The Guidelines are accompanied by the Guideline Support Library (GSL), a header-only library of types and functions to implement the Core Guidelines and static checker tools for enforcing Guideline rules.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] One of the largest implementations of this is Microsoft's implementation.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] Many of the existing features in the GSL have been later integrated into the language, such as `std::byte`, smart pointers, and `std::span`.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] To give compiler vendors greater freedom, the C++ standards committee decided not to dictate the implementation of name mangling, exception handling, and other implementation-specific features.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] The downside of this decision is that object code produced by different compilers is expected to be incompatible.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] There are, however, attempts to standardize compilers for particular machines or operating systems.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] For example, the Itanium C++ ABI is processor-independent (despite its name) and is implemented by GCC and Clang.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] C++ is often considered to be a superset of C but this is not strictly true.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] Most C code can easily be made to compile correctly in C++ but there are a few differences that cause some valid C code to be invalid or behave differently in C++.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] For example, C allows implicit conversion from `void*` to other pointer types but C++ does not (for type safety reasons).
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] Also, C++ defines many new keywords, such as `new` and `class`, which may be used as identifiers (for example, variable names) in a C program.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] Some incompatibilities have been removed by the 1999 revision of the C standard (C99), which now supports C++ features such as line comments (`//`) and declarations mixed with code.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] Some of the C99-introduced features were included in the subsequent version of the C++ standard, C++11 (out of those which were not redundant).
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] However, the C++11 standard introduces new incompatibilities, such as disallowing assignment of a string literal to a character pointer, which remains valid C.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] To intermix C and C++ code, any function declaration or definition that is to be called from/used both in C and C++ must be declared with C linkage by placing it within an `extern "C" {/*...*/}` block.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] Such a function may not rely on features depending on name mangling (i.e., function overloading).
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] Programs developed in C or C++ often utilize inline assembly to take advantage of its low-level functionalities, greater speed, and enhanced control compared to high-level programming languages when optimizing for performance is essential.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] C++ provides support for embedding assembly language using asm declarations, but the compatibility of inline assembly varies significantly between compilers and architectures.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] Unlike high-level language features such as Python or Java, assembly code is highly dependent on the underlying processor and compiler implementation.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] Different C++ compilers implement inline assembly in distinct ways.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] C++ provides two primary methods of integrating ASM code: standalone assembly files, where assembly code is written separately and linked with C++ code.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/c] And inline assembly, where assembly code is embedded within C++ code using compiler-specific extensions.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Generic programming was introduced to the mainstream with Ada in 1977.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] With templates in C++, generic programming became part of the repertoire of professional library design.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The techniques were further improved and *parameterized types* were introduced in the influential 1994 book *Design Patterns*.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] New techniques were introduced by Andrei Alexandrescu in his 2001 book *Modern C++ Design: Generic Programming and Design Patterns Applied*.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Subsequently, D implemented the same ideas.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Such software entities are known as *generics* in Ada, C#, Delphi, Eiffel, F#, Java, Mojo, Nim, Python, Go, Rust, Swift, TypeScript, and Visual Basic (.NET).
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] They are known as *parametric polymorphism* in ML, Scala, Julia, and Haskell.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The "generic programming" paradigm is an approach to software decomposition whereby fundamental requirements on types are abstracted from across concrete examples of algorithms and data structures and formalized as concepts, analogously to the abstraction of algebraic theories in abstract algebra.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Early examples of this programming approach were implemented in Scheme and Ada, although the best known example is the Standard Template Library (STL), which developed a theory of iterators that is used to decouple sequence data structures and the algorithms operating on them.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For example, given *N* sequence data structures, e.g. singly linked list, vector etc., and *M* algorithms to operate on them, e.g.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] `find`, `sort` etc., a direct approach would implement each algorithm specifically for each data structure, giving *N* × *M* combinations to implement.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Thus, only *N* + *M* data structure-algorithm combinations need be implemented.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] An important point is that a data structure will return a model of the most general concept that can be implemented efficiently—computational complexity requirements are explicitly part of the concept definition.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] This limits the data structures a given algorithm can be applied to and such complexity requirements are a major determinant of data structure choice.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Generic programming similarly has been applied in other domains, e.g. graph algorithms.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Although this approach often uses language features of compile-time genericity and templates, it is independent of particular language-technical details.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] — Alexander Stepanov, An Interview with A.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Other programming paradigms that have been described as generic programming include *Datatype generic programming* as described in "Generic Programming – an Introduction".
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The *Scrap your boilerplate* approach is a lightweight generic programming approach for Haskell.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] In this article we distinguish the high-level programming paradigms of *generic programming*, above, from the lower-level programming language *genericity mechanisms* used to implement them (see Programming language support for genericity).
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For further discussion and comparison of generic programming paradigms, see.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Genericity facilities have existed in high-level languages since at least the 1970s in languages such as ML, CLU and Ada, and were subsequently adopted by many object-based and object-oriented languages, including BETA, C++, D, Eiffel, Java, and DEC's now defunct Trellis-Owl.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Genericity is implemented and supported differently in various programming languages; the term "generic" has also been used differently in various programming contexts.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For example, in Forth the compiler can execute code while compiling and one can create new *compiler keywords* and new implementations for those words on the fly.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] It has few *words* that expose the compiler behaviour and therefore naturally offers *genericity* capacities that, however, are not referred to as such in most Forth texts.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The term has been used in functional programming, specifically in Haskell-like languages, which use a structural type system where types are always parametric and the actual code on those types is generic.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] These uses still serve a similar purpose of code-saving and rendering an abstraction.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Arrays and structs can be viewed as predefined generic types.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Every usage of an array or struct type instantiates a new concrete type, or reuses a previous instantiated type.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Array element types and struct element types are parameterized types, which are used to instantiate the corresponding generic type.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] All this is usually built-in in the compiler and the syntax differs from other generic constructs.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Some extensible programming languages try to unify built-in and user defined generic types.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] A broad survey of genericity mechanisms in programming languages follows.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For a specific survey comparing suitability of mechanisms for generic programming, see.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] When creating container classes in statically typed languages, it is inconvenient to write specific implementations for each datatype contained, especially if the code for each datatype is virtually identical.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Above, `T` is a placeholder for whatever type is specified when the list is created.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] These "generic objects of type `T`", commonly called templates, allow a class to be reused with different datatypes as long as certain contracts such as subtypes and signature are kept.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] This genericity mechanism should not be confused with *inclusion polymorphism*, which is the algorithmic usage of exchangeable sub-classes: for instance, a list of objects of type `MovingEntity` containing objects of type `Animal` and `Car`.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The C++ `template` construct used above is widely cited as the genericity construct that popularized the notion among programmers and language designers and supports many generic programming idioms.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The D language also offers fully generic-capable templates based on the C++ precedent but with a simplified syntax.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The Java language has provided genericity facilities syntactically based on C++'s since the introduction of Java Platform, Standard Edition (J2SE) 5.0.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] C# 2.0, Oxygene 1.5 (formerly Chrome) and Visual Basic (.NET) 2005 have constructs that exploit the support for generics present in Microsoft .NET Framework since version 2.0.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Ada has had generics since it was first designed in 1977–1980.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The standard library uses generics to provide many services.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Ada 2005 adds a comprehensive generic container library to the standard library, which was inspired by C++'s Standard Template Library.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] A *generic unit* is a package or a subprogram that takes one or more *generic formal parameters*.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] A *generic formal parameter* is a value, a variable, a constant, a type, a subprogram, or even an instance of another, designated, generic unit.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For generic formal types, the syntax distinguishes between discrete, floating-point, fixed-point, access (pointer) types, etc.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Some formal parameters can have default values.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] To *instantiate* a generic unit, the programmer passes *actual* parameters for each formal.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The generic instance then behaves just like any other unit.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] It is possible to instantiate generic units at run-time, for example, inside a loop.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The language syntax allows precise specification of constraints on generic formal parameters.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For example, it is possible to specify that a generic formal type will only accept a modular type as the actual.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] In this example, `Array_Type` is constrained by both `Index_Type` and `Element_Type`.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] When instantiating the unit, the programmer must pass an actual array type that satisfies these constraints.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The disadvantage of this fine-grained control is a complicated syntax, but, because all generic formal parameters are completely defined in the specification, the compiler can instantiate generics without looking at the body of the generic.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Unlike C++, Ada does not allow specialised generic instances, and requires that all generics be instantiated explicitly.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] C++ uses templates to enable generic programming techniques.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The C++ Standard Library includes the Standard Template Library or STL that provides a framework of templates for common data structures and algorithms.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Templates in C++ may also be used for template metaprogramming, which is a way of pre-evaluating some of the code at compile-time rather than run-time.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Using template specialization, C++ Templates are Turing complete.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] There are many kinds of templates, the most common being function templates and class templates.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] A *function template* is a pattern for creating ordinary functions based upon the parameterizing types supplied when instantiated.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For example, the C++ Standard Template Library contains the function template `std::max(x, y)` that creates functions that return either `x` or `y`, whichever is larger.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The compiler examines the arguments used to call `max` and determines that this is a call to `max(int, int)`.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] This works whether the arguments `x` and `y` are integers, strings, or any other type for which the expression `x < y` is sensible, or more specifically, for any type for which `operator<` is defined.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Common inheritance is not needed for the set of types that can be used, and so it is very similar to duck typing.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] A program defining a custom data type can use operator overloading to define the meaning of `<` for that type, thus allowing its use with the `std::max()` function template.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] While this may seem a minor benefit in this isolated example, in the context of a comprehensive library like the STL it allows the programmer to get extensive functionality for a new data type, just by defining a few operators for it.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Merely defining `<` allows a type to be used with the standard `std::sort()`, `std::stable_sort()`, and `std::binary_search()` algorithms or to be put inside data structures such as `std::set<T>`s (equivalent to `TreeSet<T>`, heaps, and associative arrays.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] C++ templates are completely type safe at compile time.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] As a demonstration, the standard type `std::complex<T>` does not define the `<` operator, because there is no strict order on complex numbers.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Therefore, `std::max(x, y)` will fail with a compile error, if `x` and `y` are `complex` values.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Likewise, other templates that rely on `<` cannot be applied to `complex` data unless a comparison (in the form of a functor or function) is provided.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For instance, `std::complex<T>` cannot be used as key for a `std::map<K, V>` (equivalent to `TreeMap<K, V>`) unless a comparison is provided.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Unfortunately, compilers historically generate somewhat esoteric, long, and unhelpful error messages for this sort of error.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Ensuring that a certain object adheres to a method protocol can alleviate this issue.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Languages which use `std::compare` instead of `<` can also use `std::complex<T>` values as keys.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Another kind of template, a *class template*, extends the same concept to classes.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] A class template specialization is a class.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Class templates are often used to make generic containers.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For example, the STL has a doubly linked list container, `std::list<T>` (equivalent to `LinkedList<T>`).
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] To make a linked list of integers, one writes `list<int>`, while a list of strings is denoted `list<string>`.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] A `std::list<T>` has a set of standard functions associated with it, that work for any compatible parameterizing types.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] C++20 introduces constraining template types using concepts.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] A powerful feature of C++'s templates is *template specialization*.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] This allows alternative implementations to be provided based on certain characteristics of the parameterized type that is being instantiated.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Template specialization has two purposes: to allow certain forms of optimization, and to reduce code bloat.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For example, consider a `sort()` template function.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] One of the primary activities that such a function does is to swap or exchange the values in two of the container's positions.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] If the values are large (in terms of the number of bytes it takes to store each of them), then it is often quicker to first build a separate list of pointers to the objects, sort those pointers, and then build the final sorted sequence.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] If the values are quite small however it is usually fastest to just swap the values in-place as needed.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Furthermore, if the parameterized type is already of some pointer-type, then there is no need to build a separate pointer array.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Template specialization allows the template creator to write different implementations and to specify the characteristics that the parameterized type(s) must have for each implementation to be used.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Unlike function templates, class templates can be partially specialized.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] That means that an alternate version of the class template code can be provided when some of the template parameters are known, while leaving other template parameters generic.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] This can be used, for example, to create a default implementation (the *primary specialization*) that assumes that copying a parameterizing type is expensive and then create partial specializations for types that are cheap to copy, thus increasing overall efficiency.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Clients of such a class template just use specializations of it without needing to know whether the compiler used the primary specialization or some partial specialization in each case.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Class templates can also be *fully specialized,* which means that an alternate implementation can be provided when all of the parameterizing types are known.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Some uses of templates, such as the `max()` function, were formerly filled by function-like preprocessor macros (a legacy of the C language).
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Macros are expanded (copy pasted) by the preprocessor, before program compiling; templates are actual real functions.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Macros are always expanded inline; templates can also be inline functions when the compiler deems it appropriate.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] However, templates are generally considered an improvement over macros for these purposes.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Templates avoid some of the common errors found in code that makes heavy use of function-like macros, such as evaluating parameters with side effects twice.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Perhaps most importantly, templates were designed to be applicable to much larger problems than macros.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Many compilers historically had poor support for templates, thus the use of templates could make code somewhat less portable.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Support may also be poor when a C++ compiler is being used with a linker that is not C++-aware, or when attempting to use templates across shared library boundaries.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Compilers can produce confusing, long, and sometimes unhelpful error messages when errors are detected in code that uses SFINAE.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] This can make templates difficult to develop with.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Finally, the use of templates requires the compiler to generate a separate *instance* of the templated class or function for every type parameters used with it.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] (This is necessary because types in C++ are not all the same size, and the sizes of data fields are important to how classes work.) So the indiscriminate use of templates can lead to code bloat, resulting in excessively large executables.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] However, judicious use of template specialization and derivation can dramatically reduce such code bloat in some cases:So, can derivation be used to reduce the problem of code replicated because templates are used?
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] This would involve deriving a template from an ordinary class.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] This technique proved successful in curbing code bloat in real use.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Templated classes or functions may require an *explicit specialization* of the template class which would require rewriting of an entire class for a specific template parameters used by it.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The extra instantiations generated by templates can also cause some debuggers to have difficulty working gracefully with templates.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For example, setting a debug breakpoint within a template from a source file may either miss setting the breakpoint in the actual instantiation desired or may set a breakpoint in every place the template is instantiated.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Also, the implementation source code for the template must be completely available (e.g. included in a header) to the translation unit (source file) using it.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Templates, including much of the Standard Library, if not included in header files, cannot be compiled.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] (This is in contrast to non-templated code, which may be compiled to binary, providing only a declarations header file for code using it.) This may be a disadvantage by exposing the implementing code, which removes some abstractions, and could restrict its use in closed-source projects.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The D language supports templates based in design on C++.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Templates in D use a different syntax than in C++: whereas in C++ template parameters are wrapped in angular brackets (`Template<param1, param2>`), D uses an exclamation sign and parentheses: `Template!(param1, param2)`.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] This avoids the C++ parsing difficulties due to ambiguity with comparison operators.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] If there is only one parameter, the parentheses can be omitted.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Conventionally, D combines the above features to provide compile-time polymorphism using trait-based generic programming.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Combining the above allows generating code based on existing declarations.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For example, D serialization frameworks can enumerate a type's members and generate specialized functions for each serialized type to perform serialization and deserialization.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] User-defined attributes could further indicate serialization rules.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The `import` expression and compile-time function execution also allow efficiently implementing domain-specific languages.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Generic classes have been a part of Eiffel since the original method and language design.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The foundation publications of Eiffel, use the term *genericity* to describe creating and using generic classes.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Generic classes are declared with their class name and a list of one or more *formal generic parameters*.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The formal generic parameters are placeholders for arbitrary class names that will be supplied when a declaration of the generic class is made, as shown in the two *generic derivations* below, where `ACCOUNT` and `DEPOSIT` are other class names.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] `ACCOUNT` and `DEPOSIT` are considered *actual generic parameters* as they provide real class names to substitute for `G` in actual use.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Within the Eiffel type system, although class `LIST [G]` is considered a class, it is not considered a type.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] However, a generic derivation of `LIST [G]` such as `LIST [ACCOUNT]` is considered a type.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For the list class shown above, an actual generic parameter substituting for `G` can be any other available class.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] To constrain the set of classes from which valid actual generic parameters can be chosen, a *generic constraint* can be specified.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] In the declaration of class `SORTED_LIST` below, the generic constraint dictates that any valid actual generic parameter will be a class that inherits from class `COMPARABLE`.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The generic constraint ensures that elements of a `SORTED_LIST` can in fact be sorted.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Support for the *generics*, or "containers-of-type-T" was added to the Java programming language in 2004 as part of J2SE 5.0.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] In Java, generics are only checked at compile time for type correctness.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The generic type information is then removed via a process called type erasure, to maintain compatibility with old JVM implementations, making it unavailable at runtime.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For example, a `List<String>` is converted to the raw type `java.util.List`.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The compiler inserts type casts to convert the elements to the `java.lang.String` type when they are retrieved from the list, reducing performance compared to other implementations such as C++ templates.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Generics were added as part of .NET Framework 2.0 in November 2005, based on a research prototype from Microsoft Research started in 1999.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Although similar to generics in Java, .NET generics do not apply type erasure, but implement generics as a first class mechanism in the runtime using reification.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] This design choice provides additional functionality, such as allowing reflection with preservation of generic types, and alleviating some of the limits of erasure (such as being unable to create generic arrays).
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] This also means that there is no performance hit from runtime casts and normally expensive boxing conversions.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] When primitive and value types are used as generic arguments, they get specialized implementations, allowing for efficient generic collections and methods.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] As in C++ and Java, nested generic types such as `Dictionary<string, List<int>>` are valid types, however are advised against for member signatures in code analysis design rules.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] .NET allows six varieties of generic type constraints using the `where` keyword including restricting generic types to be value types, to be classes, to have constructors, and to implement interfaces.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The `MakeAtLeast()` method allows operation on arrays, with elements of generic type `T`.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The method's type constraint indicates that the method is applicable to any type `T` that implements the generic `System.IComparable<T>` interface.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] This ensures a compile time error, if the method is called if the type does not support comparison.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The interface provides the generic method `CompareTo(T)`.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The above method could also be written without generic types, simply using the non-generic `System.Array` type.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] However, since arrays are contravariant, the casting would not be type safe, and the compiler would be unable to find certain possible errors that would otherwise be caught when using generic types.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] In addition, the method would need to access the array items as `object`s instead, and would require casting to compare two elements.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] A notable behavior of static members in a generic .NET class is static member instantiation per run-time type (see example below).
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For Pascal, generics were first implemented in 2006, in the implementation Free Pascal.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The Object Pascal dialect Delphi acquired generics in the 2007 Delphi 11 release by CodeGear, initially only with the .NET compiler (since discontinued) before being added to the native code in the 2009 Delphi 12 release.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The semantics and abilities of Delphi generics are largely modelled on those of generics in .NET 2.0, though the implementation is by necessity quite different.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] As with C#, methods and whole types can have one or more type parameters.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] In the example, TArray is a generic type (defined by the language) and MakeAtLeast a generic method.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The available constraints are very similar to the available constraints in C#: any value type, any class, a specific class or interface, and a class with a parameterless constructor.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Multiple constraints act as an additive union.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Free Pascal implemented generics in 2006 in version 2.2.0, before Delphi and with different syntax and semantics.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] However, since FPC version 2.6.0, the Delphi-style syntax is available when using the language mode `{$mode Delphi}`.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Thus, Free Pascal code supports generics in either style.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The type class mechanism of Haskell supports generic programming.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] All the necessary methods will be "derived" – that is, constructed automatically – based on the structure of the type.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] This results in an equality function (`==`) and a string representation function (`show`) being automatically defined for any type of the form `BinTree T` provided that `T` itself supports those operations.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Ralf Hinze (2004) has shown that a similar effect can be achieved for user-defined type classes by certain programming techniques.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Other researchers have proposed approaches to this and other kinds of genericity in the context of Haskell and extensions to Haskell (discussed below).
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] PolyP was the first generic programming language extension to Haskell.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] In PolyP, generic functions are called *polytypic*.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The language introduces a special construct in which such polytypic functions can be defined via structural induction over the structure of the pattern functor of a regular datatype.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Regular datatypes in PolyP are a subset of Haskell datatypes.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] A regular datatype t must be of kind ** → **, and if *a* is the formal type argument in the definition, then all recursive calls to *t* must have the form *t a*.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] These restrictions rule out higher-kinded datatypes and nested datatypes, where the recursive calls are of a different form.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Generic Haskell is another extension to Haskell, developed at Utrecht University in the Netherlands.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The resulting type-indexed value can be specialized to any type.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Clean offers generic programming based PolyP and the Generic Haskell as supported by the GHC ≥ 6.0.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] It parametrizes by kind as those but offers overloading.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Languages in the ML family support generic programming through parametric polymorphism and generic modules called *functors.* Both Standard ML and OCaml provide functors, which are similar to class templates and to Ada's generic packages.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Scheme syntactic abstractions also have a connection to genericity – these are in fact a superset of C++ templates.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] A Verilog module may take one or more parameters, to which their actual values are assigned upon the instantiation of the module.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] One example is a generic register array where the array width is given via a parameter.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Such an array, combined with a generic wire vector, can make a generic buffer or memory module with an arbitrary bit width out of a single module implementation.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] VHDL, being derived from Ada, also has generic abilities.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] C has a feature called "type-generic expressions" using the `_Generic` keyword: This feature gives C function overloading capabilities, but is not related to generic programming.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Generic programming can be achieved by using the preprocessor to define the generic code, with macro expansion taking the role of *instantiation*.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Sometimes, the non-standard extension "statement expressions" is used to simulate function-like behaviour for generic code.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] The format string is encoded as a template language consisting of verbatim text and *format specifiers* that each specify how to serialize a value.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] As the format string is processed left-to-right, a subsequent value is used for each format specifier found.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] A format specifier starts with a `%` character and has one or more following characters that specify how to serialize a value.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] The standard library provides other, similar functions that form a family of *printf-like* functions.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] The functions share the same formatting capabilities but provide different behavior such as output to a different destination or safety measures that limit exposure to vulnerabilities.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] Functions of the printf-family have been implemented in other computer programming contexts (i.e., programming languages) with the same or similar syntax and semantics.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] The scanf() C standard library function complements printf by providing formatted input (a.k.a. lexing, a.k.a. parsing) via a similar format string syntax.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] The name, *printf*, is short for *print formatted* where *print* refers to output to a printer although the function is not limited to printer output.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] Today, print refers to output to any text-based environment such as a terminal or a file.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] Early programming languages like Fortran used special statements with different syntax from other calculations to build formatting descriptions.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] Its library included the `writef` routine which looked like any other function call.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] Using normal function syntax for the printing simplifies the language, and allows the printing to be implemented in the language itself.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] In most newer languages of that era I/O is not part of the syntax.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] However the format was usually not checked to see if it matched the type (or even the number) of values being printed.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] In 1973, `printf` was included as a C standard library routine as part of Version 4 Unix.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] In 1990, the `printf` shell command, modeled after the C standard library function, was included with 4.3BSD-Reno.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] In 2004, Java 5.0 (1.5) released, which extended the class `java.io.PrintStream`, adding a method named `printf()` which functions analogously to `printf()` in C.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] Thus to print a formatted string to the standard output stream, one uses `System.out.printf()`.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] Java further introduced the method `format` to its string class `java.lang.String`.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] The need to do something about the range of problems resulting from lack of type safety has prompted attempts to make compilers `printf`-aware.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] The -Wformat option of GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) allows compile time checks to `printf` calls, enabling the compiler to detect a subset of invalid calls (and issue either a warning or an error, terminating compilation, as set by other flags).
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] Because the compiler inspects `printf` format specifiers, this feature effectively extends static analysis in C to include formatting aspects.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] C++ added input/output support using the << operator to avoid safety issues of printf.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] This used the type of the arguments to choose which code to execute to print them, avoiding the crashes that are possible with format strings.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] However, the syntax can be verbose (especially for setting options like precision), and printf remains available in C++ and is often used instead.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] C++20 added a new API which uses a string consisting of verbatim text and placeholders followed by the values to print.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] The recommended implementation is from Victor Zverovich's *fmtlib* which at compile time converts the string and argument types into an optimized formatting object, this is type-safe and syntax errors are detected at compile time.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] C++23 introduced the functions `std::print()` and `std::println()` which combined formatting and outputting, and is therefore a functional replacement for `printf()`.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] It is possible to make a translator from a printf %-string to the same formatting object and this could produce a type-safe printf, but this was also not added to the spec.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] No analogous scanf modernization has been introduced, though one has been proposed based on *scnlib*.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] These functions (plus `std::to_chars`) can print floating point accurately using the least number of trailing digits possible, an ability long missing from printf.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] Another useful feature is that they ignore the locale.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] Formatting of a value is specified as markup in the format string.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] For example, the following outputs `Your age is` and then the value of the variable *age* in decimal format.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] If included, then matching specifiers to values is *not* sequential.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] The numeric value n selects the n-th value parameter.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] This field allows for using the same value multiple times in a format string instead of having to pass the value multiple times.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] If a specifier includes this field, then subsequent specifiers must also.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] This field is very useful for localizing messages to different natural languages that use different word orders.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] In the Windows API, support for this feature is via a different function, `printf_p`.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] The width field specifies the *minimum* number of characters to output.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] If the value can be represented in fewer characters, then the value is left-padded with spaces so that output is the number of characters specified.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] If the value requires more characters, then the output is longer than the specified width.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] For example, `printf("%3d", 12);` specifies a width of 3 and outputs 12 with a space on the left to output 3 characters.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] The call `printf("%3d", 1234);` outputs 1234 which is 4 characters long since that is the minimum width for that value even though the width specified is 3.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] If the width field is omitted, the output is the minimum number of characters for the value.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] If the field is specified as `*`, then the width value is read from the list of values in the call.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] For example, `printf("%*d", 3, 10);` outputs 10 (<space>10) where the second parameter, `3`, is the width (matches with `*`) and `10` is the value to serialize (matches with `d`).
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] Though not part of the width field, a leading zero is interpreted as the zero-padding flag mentioned above, and a negative value is treated as the positive value in conjunction with the left-alignment `-` flag also mentioned above.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] The width field can be used to format values as a table (tabulated output).
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] But, columns do not align if any value is larger than fits in the width specified.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] For example, notice that the last line value (1234) does not fit in the first column of width 3 and therefore the column is not aligned.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] The precision field usually specifies a *maximum* limit of the output, as set by the formatting type.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] For floating-point numeric types, it specifies the number of digits to the right of the decimal point to which the output should be rounded; for `%g` and `%G` it specifies the total number of significant figures (before and after the decimal, not including leading or trailing zeroes) to round to.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] For the string type, it limits the number of characters that should be output, after which the string is truncated.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] The precision field may be omitted, or a numeric integer value, or a dynamic value when passed as another argument when indicated by an asterisk (`*`).
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] ISO C99 includes the `inttypes.h` header file that includes a number of macros for cross-platform `printf` coding.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] For example: `printf("%" PRId64, t);` specifies decimal format for a 64-bit signed integer.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] Since the macros evaluate to a string literal, and the compiler concatenates adjacent string literals, the expression `"%" PRId64` compiles to a single string.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] A common way to handle formatting with a custom data type is to format the custom data type value into a string, then use the `%s` specifier to include the serialized value in a larger message.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] Some printf-like functions allow extensions to the escape-character-based mini-language, thus allowing the programmer to use a specific formatting function for non-builtin types.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] One is the (now deprecated) glibc's `register_printf_function()`.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] However, it is rarely used due to the fact that it conflicts with static format string checking.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] Another is Vstr custom formatters, which allows adding multi-character format names.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] Some applications (like the Apache HTTP Server) include their own printf-like function, and embed extensions into it.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] However these all tend to have the same problems that `register_printf_function()` has.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] The Linux kernel `printk` function supports a number of ways to display kernel structures using the generic `%p` specification, by *appending* additional format characters.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] For example, `%pI4` prints an IPv4 address in dotted-decimal form.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] This allows static format string checking (of the `%p` portion) at the expense of full compatibility with normal printf.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] Extra value arguments are ignored, but if the format string has more format specifiers than value arguments passed, the behavior is undefined.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] For some C compilers, an extra format specifier results in consuming a value even though there isn't one which allows the format string attack.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] Generally, for C, arguments are passed on the stack.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] If too few arguments are passed, then printf can read past the end of the stack frame, thus allowing an attacker to read the stack.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] Some compilers, like the GNU Compiler Collection, will statically check the format strings of printf-like functions and warn about problems (when using the flags -Wall or -Wformat).
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] GCC will also warn about user-defined printf-style functions if the non-standard "format" `__attribute__` is applied to the function.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] The format string is often a string literal, which allows static analysis of the function call.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] However, the format string can be the value of a variable, which allows for dynamic formatting but also a security vulnerability known as an uncontrolled format string exploit.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] Although an output function on the surface, `printf` allows writing to a memory location specified by an argument via `%n`.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] This functionality can be used for code injection attacks without violating control-flow integrity.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] The `%n` format specifier also makes `printf` accidentally Turing-complete even with a well-formed set of arguments.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] A game of tic-tac-toe written in the format string is a winner of the 27th IOCCC.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] Variants of `printf` in the C standard library include: `fprintf` outputs to a file instead of standard output.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] `sprintf` writes to a string buffer instead of standard output.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] `snprintf` provides a level of safety over `sprintf` since the caller provides a length *n* that is the length of the output buffer in bytes (including space for the trailing null character).
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] `asprintf` provides for safety by accepting a string handle (`char**`) argument.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] The function allocates a buffer of sufficient size to contain the formatted text and outputs the buffer via the handle.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] For each function of the family, including printf, there is also a variant that accepts a single `va_list` argument rather than a variable list of arguments.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] Typically, these variants start with "v".
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] For example: `vprintf`, `vfprintf`, `vsprintf`.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] Generally, printf-like functions return the number of bytes output or -1 to indicate failure.
[src:fmt-cpp-lib/printf-format-string] The following list includes notable programming languages that provide (directly or via a standard library) functioning that is the same or similar to the C printf-like functions.
